## Part 1: "Hello world" and setting up an environment
 
First of all, let's install [Webstorm](https://www.jetbrains.com/webstorm/) Javascript IDE as an editor for our project, which is a very convenient tool for developing js applications and has ES6 syntax support. 
Next step is to install node.js. As I am a windows user, I have installed it from [here](https://nodejs.org/en/download/) and nvm (Node version manager) - from [here](https://github.com/coreybutler/nvm-windows). Note that, first you need to install node and then nvm.

Now, let's create a new blank(empty) project from Webstorm. If we want to check that if node.js is correctly installed, run Webstorm terminal (alt + F12) and check with entering a command node -v and nvm -v. 

Now, to set up dependecies, we need to run `npm init`
This will ask you some questions, and then write a package.json for you. In the end the package.json looks like this:

    {
      "name": "untitled2",
      "version": "1.0.0",
      "description": "",
      "main": "index.js",
      "dependencies": {},
      "devDependencies": {},
      "scripts": {
        "test": "echo \"Error: no test specified\" && exit 1"
      },
      "author": "",
      "license": "ISC"
    }

